9.
mid = (low + high) >> 1 is similar to (low + high) // 2 for non-negative ints, used in binary search
right shifting >> is dividing by 2 (floor for non-negative), and left shifting << is multiplying by 2
left shifting is adding zeroes to the right of the 1 bit, for example 1 << 3 is 1000 which equals 8
right shifting is removing the zeroes at the right:
For example:
Right shifting 1010 (which is 10 in decimal) by 1 position (1010 >> 1) results in 0101 (which is 5 in decimal).
Right shifting 1100 (which is 12 in decimal) by 2 positions (1100 >> 2) results in 0011 (which is 3 in decimal).

